projectInfo.description:
In the region of Ituri, disease oubreaks and violence followed by population movements are recurrent. The mortality and morbidity rates are high and some health areas are particularly isolated. This isolation is due to the lack of accessible roads and lack of communication means. Also the security in the area complicates the acces to healthcare. 

International actors in the region have limited capacity to deal with sudden emergencies in terms of personnel, inventory or logistics. Thus, a detailed mapping of these areas would provide a better understanding and would greatly help to reduce the mortality and morbidity associated with medico-humanitarian emergencies.
projectInfo.instructions:
Imagery
========================
Please use **Esri World Imagery** as a base in this task, but feel free to compare with any other imagery. 

Roads
=========================
We will focus on mapping **roads**.  The most important thing is to maintain consistency in the network. **Every road should connect to another of greater importance.**

Use for roads:
- *highway=residential* inside residential areas 
- *highway=unclassified* or *Minor routes*  for roads connecting smaller villages and hamlets
- *highway=tertiary*, *highway=secondary* or *highway=primary* are used for main roads that connect towns. **You should NOT use them for this project, they are already mapped.** 

Also smaller offshoot roads can be left off for the purposes of this task. However, if you want to map them, use the following tags:

- *“highway=track* or *Unmaintained Track Road* for roads which connect *fields and farmland* or are leading just to rivers and ponds
- *highway=path* for roads too narrow for a 4-wheel drive vehicle to pass (within and outside residential areas

See [Highway Africa Tagging Guidelines](https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Highway_Tag_Africa) for more advice on tagging roads in East Africa.

Mapping hints
========
- **Be as precise as possible** - This takes a little bit of practice, but following a road closely really makes a difference in the quality of map data produced. Quality is more important than quantity when it comes to mapping. Zooming in close helps.
- **Split roads** - You will be mapping different roads with different classifications. Split your roads on crossings and/or where you change the road classification.
- **Connect roads to roads** - Always connect roads to other roads where they meet and never end roads on landuse or other area polygon edges.
- **Map roads hidden under trees** - Short segments of a road or path that you cannot see through the trees/buildings but seem very likely to exist should be mapped to keep the road network complete.
- **Map a bit outside your square** - Map a little beyond your task square so the person who maps the task square next to yours can easily connect to your road.
- **It is ok to "split" task squares** - Sometimes a task square will have a lot detailed settlement mapping. If you think it would help to make the task square smaller so the mapping could be finished in a more reasonable time, use the "split" link above the task square comment box.
- **Sometimes a task square is already mapped** - Sometimes you will find a task square that looks totally mapped or has nothing in it to map. Just double check that it is complete, map anything that was missed, straighten up anything that needs it and then mark it "Done".
- **Ask questions** - if you have questions, please ask. Yo can post questions in the *Questions and Comments* tab of this task, or if you are at a mapping event, check with your neighbour or just raise your hand and ask.
